content.description:
Two quality mantles on the backside of the Vomitorium.

The left line starts on two sloper knobs with bad feet. Maybe the harder of the two. Start static!

The right line starts on decent edges with a jug foot.
content.location: On the backside of the Vomitorium slabs.

content.description: This face climb starts off using small knobs, easing up to some nice smearing to the top.  Bolts are on the top, but one has to climb the route to get at them.
content.location: Just past the Columbo Crack, one can tunnel through the two adjoining boulders and view this on the immediate right.

content.description: A slanting offwidth rising out of the bushes. Wide at the bottom, then a mantle to top out.
content.protection: If you lead it, large cams for the bottom and small cams or nuts for the top. Otherwise, a properly placed boulder pad will do.
content.location: This is the same crack as Colombo Crack, but on the opposite side of the boulder.

content.description: This low angled face has a start that is deceptively difficult if climbed in an obvious direct fashion.  A small incut for the fingers, with two tough smears gets one up to another shallow incut.  A couple more moves to the top.
content.location: Just past the Columbo Crack, one can tunnel through two adjoining boulders and view this straight ahead.  This is the rock left of Vomitorium.

content.description: Tower Two face is a top rop problem on the face to the right of the crack. This is a fun climb easy for the grade. Follow the natural holds going up the face. A good climb to work on after leading the chimney and the crack.
content.protection: Top rope bolt anchor at top of rock. Use rap rings to get off rock.

content.description: On the west side of Tower Two you will see a crack. The start is a large opening with a stair like formation for getting into the crack. The start is a little akward for 5.7 (look for the hold in the horizontal crack to the right)The climb takes good pro and is a good route for a begining leader.
content.protection: Use a 3 or 4 to protect the start. .5-2 cams for climb. Bolt Anchors at top of rock.

content.description: WEAR PANTS! This climb is good training for doing chimneys. The start is akward but once you are in the chimney the climbing is good and there are opportunities for pro. The crux is exiting the chimney onto a small ledge. The route finishes with a low angle hand crack. If you top rope this climb use a directional in the hand crack.
content.protection: The climb takes small to medium size cams in cracks in the chimney. If you have a number 5 cam it will fit in the back of the chimney after the start. You can use a #3 to protect the move getting into the chimney. However, this is not mandatory. Bolt Anchors and rap rings at the top of Tower Two.

content.description: Super thin friction edging/friction problem
content.location: The utterly blank boulder just uphill from the chopper mantles (TV screen), on the right as you go up. Can be identified by the telephone pole right next to it.

content.description:
Sit start on the obvious finger lock and scrunchy feet. Make a couple heinous moves into the stand start (~5.11a on its own)

May have been done before, please correct me if so.
content.location: Above the Vomitorium. Small buttcrack boulder.

content.description: This climbs the obvious right side of the face, while always keeping the right hand on the corner/arete.
content.location: Coming up the hill one can't help but notice a boulder that literally looks like a television screen.  Up from the road about 40 feet.   See pic.

content.description:
Super Edge East

AKA Television Screen North-East Arete, Right

This climbs

the right side of

the 'Television Screen' north-east arete.

The easier, north side of the Television Sets NEÂ arete is less steep and more often done.

It is short but quite physical. Grab the arete and crank. Not much for feet.
content.protection: Pads. Landing is a little awkward with a boulder in the way. Can be TR'd; two bolt anchor.
content.location: Pass the water tower, the TV set can be seen on climbers left of the trail. For a small boulder, the climbs on this rock are great fun and a good warmup for routes further up the hill.

content.description: A great Woodson face climb on nice features. Move through slopers to a good edge, then lockoff to the lip. Originally given the rating of B1.
content.location: On the east face of TV Screen boulder, around the corner left of Woodward Arete.

content.description: This is one of only a handfull of easy and safe boulder problems at Woodson.  It is a left slanting hand crack, finishing with a nice jug/face move.
content.location: Take the trail to the Television Screen, and follow the another trail that goes left.  2 minute approach from the road.

content.description: This is the obvious looking tower just behind and left of Tower 2.  Both of these classic routes (left and right) start on the backside, and realistically must be lead (although years ago after much consternation we swung the rope over and batman'd up one side to set up a TR).  Going up and right (facing east)is definitely the easier of the two, with the left (facing west) taking a palmy, minimal feet traverse with dubious pro to a dead vertical crack (probably 5.11a).
content.protection: Thin to 2.5"  Bolts for belay/lower off
content.location: Just behind Tower Two.  Largish tower with a marshmallow shaped head on top.

content.description:
Next step after Marshmallow Tower 10c. Start on the north side of the formation and do some awkward chimney moves between the two boulders to gain the horizontal crack, place a couple pieces where you can and then bust some cruxy moves around the corner on slopers to gain the horizontal finger crack. Bad fall here, no pro through the crux- make sure you have a good belayer, a crashpad might also be a good idea.

I tried this thing about 2 years ago and it seemed impossible, but it's much easier once you figure out the secret knee bar beta. The crux is 5.11 and the finger crack is 5.10+. Falling mid crux isn't that bad, just be ready to swing into the rocks!
content.protection: Thin to .4 and doubles of .5 camalot, anchors on top.
content.location: Approach via the trail to Tower Two. You can see the Marshmallow Tower from the service road with some slime coming out of the horizontal and an obvious splitter to the top. Bolts on top to rappel.

content.description:
Start with a high reach to a sloper knob, then move straight up to the lip.

Definitely not the prettiest mantle at Woodson, but still worth a shot.
content.location: On the NE corner of the Chopper Mantle boulder. Starts on a very slopey knob.

climbs.name: Jump
climbs.fa: R. Amick, R. Allenby, M. Paul

content.description: Leap off the soloflex boulder and latch onto the prominent knob on the adjacent boulder. Hauling yourself onto the knob is the crux
content.location: The soloflex boulder is a low, rounded rock on the left side of the road 50 feet from where the trail to seminar wall takes off. Stand on the left edge of the soloflex and jump to the big knob

content.description: Classic edging and slab climbing up the smooth concave face.  A little tall but the holds get better as you move higher.
content.location: On the hillside in between 10a on the Outside and TV Screen.  There is a pretty distinct trail connecting those two boulders.  Head First is about half way between the two.

content.description: The following post also appeared in the Uncertainty Principle thread but is reposted here because the TV Screen Center is a well known long standing Woodson problem: It was an almost perfect day late in the afternoon at Woodson today. The temps went quite cool and the rock was still clean after last week's rain. Late in the afternoon John Weinberg (Johannsolo) completed the long standing problem in the center of the TV Screen. The problem, first tried by Kevin Powell in the mid 80's was previously known under the working name of "The Emergency Broadcast System". Based on the lack of any response to previous queries on this forum regarding any known ascents, coupled with various references that refer to the center problem being "V?", it is assumed that this is the first known (verified) ascent of the problem. HDTV V6. The V6 rating was felt to be appropriate because the problem was similar in nature and difficulty to that of problems in several other bouldering areas as well as the crux moves on routes at Suicide (Idyllwild).
content.location: Middle of  the Television Screen

content.description: Super cool Fang-shaped feature hanging out of a giant broken boulder. Â This huge piece somehow got stuck (somewhat recently), and floats a foot off of the ground! Â Start with good foothold at bottom of the fang, left toehook / right heelhooks get you up onto the arÃªte, good holds on each side to top out. Â (harder Crack variation on left side)
content.location:
Keep following path uphill (SW) from Slant Crack about 150ft, past a couple other big boulders, and towards the left side of formation containing a few cool little caves (and other hidden routes)

GPS: (33.004495, -116.964322)

content.description: A burly crank with overhanging start. On the east wall of the vomitorium
content.location: In the vomitorium, east side, on the west end of the same boulder that colombo crack is on

content.description: Thin fingers up the underside of this perfectly rounded boulder problem with nothing for the feet, less an initial heelhook.  This climb appears more probable than it is, and is a short but stout boulder problem/TR.
content.location: Follow the trail from Tower Two face into the bush and up to the next rock.  Going past and tunneling through to backside of the rock can give one access to climb down the rock to set up the TR

content.description: Only takes a couple of moves.  Probably not worth spending much time on, although there are a few different mantel problems on this same boulder.
content.location: Just off of the road (uphill side), downhill from the TV Screen.  Has a very gentle slope on the top, with 3 sharp but short faces.  Climbs are on the E side, NE corner and NW corner.  "Chopper Mantel" is the NW corner/side.  Can walk on/off of the S side.

content.description: Reachy start. Easy finish.
content.location: Face to the right of baby elephant. NW side.

content.description: Obvious hand crack. Climb the crack between the thick flake and the rock to hand holds above. There is also a 5.8 face to the right of the crack and a mantle way around to the left of the crack. A good warm up boulder.
content.protection: Short, just boulder it.  The landing is good.  Great when you don't have a partner.
content.location: Directly across the road from the Television Screen.  Climb is facing away from the road.
